cted behavior\n\nA bunch of logs from ./dataset.ts to be displayed.\n\n\nActual behaviour:\n```\nUncaught RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded\n    at ye (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:12476)\n    at Object.fn (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:6719)\n    at Ie (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:8342)\n    at H (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:8122)\n    at Z (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:9655)\n    at ze (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:10505)\n    at pt (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:9912)\n    at M (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:9825)\n    at Tt (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/solid-js.mjs:2:5349)\n    at i (esm.sh/solid-js@1.9.9/es2022/store.mjs:2:3258)\n```\n\nThis error doesn't happen and renders as intended when Line56 is changed to mount \\<MainPage /> Directly as opposed to having it called via the router\n\n### Screenshots or Videos\n\n<img width=\"1166\" height=\"372\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4f7d2e45-1880-40a6-8c66-979e08170547\" />\n\n<img width=\"2946\" height=\"1571\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fd1577e5-8f9d-4ea0-8046-5aca13fdb485\" />\n\n# Inside the Sandbox\n\n<img width=\"1422\" height=\"1820\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7d5ff22e-9451-4015-84b2-cb0738843ba0\" />\nAnd what its intended to look like (which is what happens when MainPage is directly rendered bypassing router)\n\n<img width=\"1461\" height=\"1487\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/1a09ee3a-6609-463e-bbf7-ca1403ae53f2\" />\n\n### Platform\n\n- OS: Windows\n- Browser: Edge\n- Version: 140.0.3485.40 \n\n\n### Additional context\n\nIn analyzing it, it is this line of code at fault\nhttps://github.com/solidjs/solid/blob/0af2c2b4dc5f7da8022c16563c25d0687f68aff3/packages/solid/src/reactive/signal.ts#L1749\nwhere it is trying to use .apply to call push in bulk, but .apply [doesn't work for large arrays](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Function/apply#:~:text=The%20consequences%20of%20calling%20a%20function%20with%20too%20many%20arguments) due to how it puts the contents on the stack.\n\nI genuinely don't know why this only blows up when Solid Router is involved and only found out when making the reproduction in the sandbox and it worked until I added it back in for the more 1:1 equivilent.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/solidjs/solid/issues/2542/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/solidjs/solid/issues/2542/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1/events","html_url":"https://github.com/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1","id":4411422328,"node_id":"I_kwDOSYcF0c8AAAABBvD2eA","number":1,"title":"PRD: Solid Doctor optimal end state","user":{"login":"erik-kroon","id":174307798,"node_id":"U_kgDOCmO51g","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/174307798?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon","html_url":"https://github.com/erik-kroon","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/erik-kroon/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":2,"created_at":"2026-05-09T06:10:40Z","updated_at":"2026-05-09T07:01:46Z","closed_at":"2026-05-09T07:01:46Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"OWNER","active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"# PRD: Solid Doctor — Oxlint-Powered Code Health for Solid’s Reactive Graph\n\nStatus: Ready for agent planning  \nScope: Optimal end-state product definition, not MVP-only  \nPrimary audience: Solid/SolidStart developers, library authors, teams adopting Solid, and AI coding agents that generate Solid code  \nPrimary inspiration: React Doctor’s one-command health-check product shape, adapted to Solid’s fine-grained reactivity and an Oxlint-first toolchain  \n\n## Source Notes\n\nThis PRD follows Matt Pocock’s `to-prd` structure: synthesize the current context without re-interviewing, define the problem and solution, include an extensive numbered user-story list, sketch major modules and deep modules, document implementation decisions, testing decisions, out-of-scope items, and further notes.\n\nKey constraints from the current product context:\n\n- The product should be meaningful for the Solid ecosystem, not merely a React ecosystem catch-up project.\n- The user likes the `solid-lint`/`solid-doctor` direction: a correctness and code-health tool for Solid’s reactivity model.\n- The user personally uses `oxfmt` and `oxlint`, so the product should feel Oxlint-native rather than ESLint-first.\n- The product should be inspired by React Doctor’s code-health scanner and score model, but should have a sharper Solid-specific thesis.\n- The most valuable diagnostic surface is “React-shaped Solid”: code that compiles but subtly misuses Solid’s fine-grained reactivity, effects, owners, stores, resources, lists, and SSR behavior.\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nSolid’s fine-grained reactive model is a major strength, but it creates a different class of code-quality failures than React. Many Solid bugs are not caused by excessive component re-renders. They are caused by values being read or copied in the wrong scope, reactive proxies being destructured, effects being used for derivation, async code assuming dependency tracking continues after `await`, owner lifetimes being lost, browser-only code leaking into server-rendered paths, or dynamic lists being rendered with React-shaped patterns.\n\nThese mistakes are especially common when developers come from React, when teams adopt Solid incrementally, and when AI coding agents generate Solid code from React-heavy training examples. Existing lint rules help, but the ecosystem lacks a single, polished, Oxlint-fast, Solid-specific “doctor” command that scans a project, explains the health of the reactive graph, groups issues by user-impact, guides fixes, supports CI, and installs coding-agent instructions that prevent the same mistakes from recurring.\n\nThe user needs a product that makes Solid’s correctness model visible and enforceable across local development, CI, code review, and agentic coding workflows.\n\n## Solution\n\nBuild **Solid Doctor**: an Oxlint-powered code-health tool for Solid and SolidStart projects that detects React-shaped Solid, scores project health, explains issues in Solid’s own vocabulary, and gives developers and agents a clear path to remediation.\n\nAt optimal end-state, Solid Doctor is not just a lint plugin. It is a product layer over a rule engine:\n\n- A one-command CLI that scans Solid/SolidStart codebases and outputs a 0–100 health score.\n- An Oxlint-compatible plugin containing Solid-specific rules.\n- A deeper semantic analyzer for rule classes that need cross-file, type-aware, or data-flow-like context.\n- A project classifier that understands Vite Solid apps, SolidStart apps, libraries, monorepos, and test fixtures.\n- A scoring engine that groups diagnostics by Solid-specific risk categories.\n- Human-readable explanations with examples, recommended fixes, and links to canonical Solid docs.\n- CI and pull-request integrations with diff mode and annotations.\n- Agent-install functionality that writes Solid-specific coding rules for Cursor, Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, and AGENTS.md workflows.\n- A fixtures and conformance suite that proves each rule catches real Solid mistakes without punishing idiomatic Solid.\n\nThe core product promise:\n\n> Your AI writes React-shaped Solid. Solid Doctor catches it.\n\nThe deeper ecosystem promise:\n\n> Make Solid’s reactive graph easier to trust, teach, debug, and enforce.\n\n## Product Principles\n\n1. **Solid-native, not React-translated.** Diagnostics should be framed around signals, stores, resources, owners, computations, JSX bindings, Suspense, and SolidStart boundaries.\n2. **Oxlint-first.** Formatting remains `oxfmt`; general linting remains `oxlint`; Solid Doctor adds Solid-specific correctness and code-health.\n3. **High signal over high volume.** A warning should usually represent a likely real bug, broken mental model, SSR problem, or production maintainability risk.\n4. **Explain the mental model.** The product should teach why a pattern is risky, not only point at syntax.\n5. **Prefer fix guidance over shame.** Each diagnostic should include the intended Solid pattern and an escape hatch when the code is deliberate.\n6. **Deep modules over shallow wrappers.** Complex analysis should be hidden behind small, stable, testable interfaces.\n7. **Agent-compatible by default.** Output should be useful to humans and coding agents.\n8. **Incremental adoption.** Large projects should be able to start with diff mode, warnings-only mode, rule groups, or score budgets.\n9. **No formatting bikeshedding.** Solid Doctor must not compete with `oxfmt`.\n10. **Respect existing ecosystem work.** Use existing Solid linting knowledge as prior art; do not duplicate existing rules unless improving scope, UX, type-awareness, or Oxlint integration.\n\n## Target Users\n\n1. **Solo Solid developers** who want fast feedback when writing components, resources, effects, stores, and SolidStart routes.\n2. **React-to-Solid migrants** who need guardrails against React-shaped patterns that compile but behave incorrectly in Solid.\n3. **SolidStart app teams** that need SSR/client-boundary checks, route-data checks, and CI enforcement.\n4. **Component library authors** who need stricter correctness guarantees for primitives, headless UI, and registry-distributed code.\n5. **AI coding-agent users** who need generated Solid code to follow Solid’s reactive mental model.\n6. **Open-source maintainers** who want project health reports, PR annotations, and quality gates without hand-reviewing every Solid antipattern.\n\n## Optimal End-State\n\nSolid Doctor becomes the default health-check layer for serious Solid projects.\n\nA developer can run one command in any Solid app or library and get a useful diagnosis:\n\n- What kind of Solid project is this?\n- What Solid version and framework setup does it use?\n- Are props, stores, signals, memos, effects, resources, lists, owners, and SSR paths being used idiomatically?\n- Which issues are correctness bugs versus maintainability smells?\n- Which issues are likely introduced in the current branch?\n- What should be fixed first?\n- Which rules should be installed into agents so the problem does not recur?\n\nIn CI, Solid Doctor can annotate pull requests, fail only on new critical issues, and publish a readable health score.\n\nIn editor/agent workflows, Solid Doctor can generate or update coding instructions that prevent common mistakes before code is written.\n\nIn ecosystem terms, Solid Doctor becomes the shared vocabulary for Solid reactivity correctness:\n\n- “reactive snapshot”\n- “async tracking gap”\n- “derived-state effect”\n- “owner leak”\n- “SSR browser global leak”\n- “React-shaped dynamic list”\n- “broad store tracking”\n- “resource-in-effect”\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n1. A new Solid project can run Solid Doctor with no manual configuration and receive an actionable health report.\n2. A SolidStart project can receive SSR-specific diagnostics without false positives in clearly client-only code.\n3. A codebase using `oxlint` can add Solid Doctor without switching to ESLint.\n4. A developer can install agent rules and see future AI-generated Solid code improve measurably.\n5. The top five rule categories catch real examples from real Solid codebases and fixture apps.\n6. The tool can run in CI and annotate PRs with only changed-branch diagnostics.\n7. Users can adopt the product incrementally through warnings-only, diff-only, category-only, and score-threshold modes.\n8. Rule docs are clear enough that a React developer can understand the Solid mental model behind each warning.\n9. The project’s rule engine has stable interfaces that make adding new rule packs possible without rewriting the CLI.\n10. The project becomes useful even for developers who already use `eslint-plugin-solid`, because the doctor layer adds scoring, grouping, explanations, CI, agent installation, cross-rule context, and deeper semantic analysis.\n\n## Domain Vocabulary\n\n- **Diagnostic**: A reported issue with severity, category, location, explanation, confidence, and remediation guidance.\n- **Health score**: A 0–100 score summarizing project health, weighted by diagnostic severity, confidence, category, and whether issues are new or pre-existing.\n- **Rule**: A single detection unit that can produce diagnostics.\n- **Rule pack**: A group of rules focused on a product area, such as reactivity, SSR, effects, resources, or owners.\n- **Reactive snapshot**: A non-reactive local value copied from a reactive source outside a tracking scope, later used as though it were live.\n- **Tracking scope**: A Solid computation or JSX binding context where signal/store/resource reads are subscribed.\n- **Owner**: Solid’s lifetime/context owner used for cleanup, context lookup, and descendant computations.\n- **Async tracking gap**: Code that assumes reactive tracking or owner context continues after an `await` when it does not.\n- **Doctor run**: A full analysis session over a project, branch diff, file set, or CI target.\n- **Project classifier**: Module that detects whether a project is Solid, SolidStart, library, monorepo, Vite app, or mixed JS/TS package.\n- **Agent install**: A command that writes Solid-specific coding instructions into supported agent configuration surfaces.\n\n## Major Modules and Deep Module Opportunities\n\n### 1. Project Classifier\n\nPurpose: Detect the project shape and select appropriate rule groups.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Detect Solid usage, SolidStart usage, Vite usage, TypeScript usage, monorepo layout, package-manager type, and source/test boundaries.\n- Classify files as app code, library code, tests, config, server-capable code, client-only code, generated code, or ignored code.\n- Expose a small interface that returns a normalized project profile.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Hide messy package/config/framework detection behind a stable `ProjectProfile` interface.\n\n### 2. Rule Engine Adapter\n\nPurpose: Let Solid Doctor run Oxlint-compatible JS plugin rules and future native rules through one product interface.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Load Solid Doctor rules.\n- Map raw linter reports into Solid Doctor diagnostics.\n- Support configuration, severity overrides, ignore patterns, and rule metadata.\n- Provide a path to native Oxlint rules later without changing the product surface.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Encapsulate the difference between JS plugin rules, native rules, and custom semantic analyzers behind a single `RuleRunner` interface.\n\n### 3. Reactive Source Model\n\nPurpose: Identify Solid reactive sources and distinguish them from ordinary functions and values.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Detect signals, stores, memos, resources, selectors, context-provided accessors, props, split/merged props, and common Solid primitives.\n- Track aliases and imports from `solid-js`, `solid-js/store`, Solid Router, SolidStart, and selected ecosystem packages.\n- Support configurable user-defined reactive primitives.\n\nDeep module opportunity: A reusable semantic model of “what is reactive” that multiple rules can query without duplicating AST heuristics.\n\n### 4. Tracking Scope Analyzer\n\nPurpose: Determine whether a reactive read occurs in a tracked, untracked, event, async, setup, JSX, effect, memo, resource, or server-only context.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Classify reads by scope.\n- Detect reads that happen before JSX returns, inside component setup, inside event handlers, inside effects, inside memos, inside resources, inside callbacks, and after `await`.\n- Detect cases where a read is deliberately untracked.\n\nDeep module opportunity: A shared `TrackingContext` interface that powers reactive snapshot, signal-read, effect, async-gap, and owner rules.\n\n### 5. Diagnostic Normalizer\n\nPurpose: Convert low-level findings into consistent, user-facing diagnostics.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Attach category, severity, confidence, message, explanation, remediation, examples, docs references, and suppress/fix guidance.\n- Deduplicate overlapping diagnostics from multiple rules.\n- Group diagnostics by file, category, severity, and changed-line status.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Centralize messaging quality and avoid every rule inventing its own UX.\n\n### 6. Scoring Engine\n\nPurpose: Produce a trustworthy 0–100 health score.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Weight diagnostics by severity, confidence, category, project type, and branch-diff status.\n- Avoid punishing large projects unfairly by normalizing across file count or analyzed surface area.\n- Provide sub-scores for reactivity, SSR, rendering, effects, owners, resources, and maintainability.\n- Support configurable score thresholds for CI.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Keep scoring separate from rule detection so score changes do not require changing rules.\n\n### 7. Reporter System\n\nPurpose: Present results to humans, CI systems, JSON consumers, and agents.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Terminal reporter.\n- JSON reporter.\n- SARIF reporter.\n- GitHub annotation reporter.\n- Markdown summary reporter.\n- Agent-readable report mode.\n\nDeep module opportunity: One normalized `DoctorReport` object can serve all output formats.\n\n### 8. Agent Instruction Installer\n\nPurpose: Generate coding-agent rules that prevent common Solid mistakes.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Detect supported agent surfaces.\n- Install or update Solid-specific instructions.\n- Include project-specific rule configuration.\n- Avoid overwriting user-authored content unsafely.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Encapsulate agent-specific file formats behind a stable `InstructionTarget` interface.\n\n### 9. Rule Documentation System\n\nPurpose: Make every diagnostic teach the Solid mental model.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Rule pages with “why this matters,” examples, fixes, false-positive notes, suppression guidance, and source references.\n- CLI `explain` command.\n- Link diagnostics to docs.\n- Provide AI-readable rule summaries.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Single source of truth for rule metadata used by CLI, website, generated agent docs, and JSON output.\n\n### 10. Fixture and Conformance Harness\n\nPurpose: Prove rule quality and prevent regressions.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- Golden fixtures for valid and invalid Solid code.\n- SolidStart fixtures for SSR/client-boundary rules.\n- Monorepo fixtures.\n- False-positive fixtures.\n- Snapshot tests for diagnostics.\n- Performance benchmarks.\n\nDeep module opportunity: Let every rule be tested against the same stable fixture API.\n\n## Rule Categories\n\n### Reactivity Correctness\n\n- Reactive prop snapshots.\n- Store destructuring snapshots.\n- Signal reads outside tracking scopes.\n- Derived state in effects.\n- Broad store tracking.\n- Missing `createMemo` for expensive or reused derivations.\n- Accidental tracking of incidental reads.\n- Misuse of default prop values that breaks liveness.\n\n### Effects and Lifecycle\n\n- Effects used for derivation.\n- Effects that read and write the same signal without guards.\n- Missing cleanup for timers, listeners, observers, subscriptions, and roots.\n- DOM APIs used before mount.\n- Fetching critical data in effects where resource/router data would be expected.\n\n### Async, Resources, and Suspense\n\n- Async tracking gaps after `await`.\n- Fetch-in-effect patterns that should be resources, router data, queries, or actions.\n- Resource source functions that track too much.\n- Missing Suspense or error boundary around async UI.\n- Overbroad invalidation or revalidation patterns.\n\n### Owner and Lifetime\n\n- `createRoot` without disposal.\n- Computations created outside an owner.\n- Async callbacks that create computations after owner context is lost.\n- Context usage that may be disconnected from owner lifetime.\n- External integrations without cleanup.\n\n### Rendering and Control Flow\n\n- Reactive dynamic lists rendered with `.map()` instead of Solid control-flow components.\n- Component setup conditionals that should be reactive conditionals.\n- Unstable children access.\n- Missing keyed reset behavior when subtree identity matters.\n- Class/style patterns that create unnecessary churn.\n\n### SSR and SolidStart\n\n- Browser globals in server-capable paths.\n- Effects used for data required by server-rendered HTML.\n- Hydration-sensitive values read during SSR without a stable fallback.\n- Request-scoped data stored in module-level mutable state.\n- Client-only libraries imported into SSR paths.\n\n### Project Health\n\n- Dead code and unused exports, optionally delegated to external tools.\n- Dependency smells relevant to Solid projects.\n- Missing Solid Doctor config or agent instructions.\n- Unsupported or risky package versions.\n\n## User Stories\n\n1. As a Solid developer, I want to run one command against my project, so that I can see whether my code contains Solid-specific correctness risks.\n2. As a Solid developer, I want a 0–100 health score, so that I can quickly understand whether my project is healthy enough to merge or release.\n3. As a Solid developer, I want diagnostics grouped by reactivity, effects, async, SSR, rendering, and owner lifetime, so that I can fix the highest-risk areas first.\n4. As a React-to-Solid migrant, I want the tool to detect React-shaped Solid patterns, so that I can learn Solid’s mental model while fixing real code.\n5. As a Solid developer, I want a diagnostic when I copy `props.foo` into a local value and later treat it as reactive, so that I do not accidentally render stale data.\n6. As a Solid developer, I want a diagnostic when I destructure a store object in a way that breaks fine-grained tracking, so that nested state remains reactive.\n7. As a Solid developer, I want a diagnostic when a signal is read outside a tracking scope and then used in JSX or derived output, so that I do not accidentally create a stale snapshot.\n8. As a Solid developer, I want derived-state effects to be flagged, so that I can replace them with accessors or memos.\n9. As a Solid developer, I want effect self-trigger loops to be detected, so that I avoid infinite loops and accidental repeated work.\n10. As a Solid developer, I want the tool to distinguish deliberate side effects from derived state, so that useful effects are not noisy.\n11. As a Solid developer, I want missing cleanup for event listeners, timers, observers, and subscriptions to be detected, so that components and roots dispose correctly.\n12. As a Solid developer, I want diagnostics for `createRoot` without a captured or called dispose function, so that I avoid owner leaks.\n13. As a Solid developer, I want async code after `await` to be analyzed for lost owner/tracking assumptions, so that I do not create invisible reactive bugs.\n14. As a Solid developer, I want resource source functions to be checked for broad dependencies, so that resources refetch only when intended.\n15. As a Solid developer, I want fetch-in-effect patterns to be flagged when route data or resources are more appropriate, so that async state integrates with Solid’s rendering model.\n16. As a SolidStart developer, I want browser globals in SSR-capable code to be detected, so that server rendering does not crash.\n17. As a SolidStart developer, I want critical data loaded in effects to be flagged, so that server-rendered pages do not ship incomplete HTML.\n18. As a SolidStart developer, I want client-only imports in server-capable paths to be detected, so that browser-only libraries do not leak into SSR bundles.\n19. As a SolidStart developer, I want request-scoped mutable module state to be flagged, so that user data does not leak across requests.\n20. As a Solid developer, I want dynamic `.map()` in reactive JSX to be flagged, so that I choose the appropriate Solid list primitive.\n21. As a Solid developer, I want the tool to distinguish static arrays from reactive arrays, so that harmless `.map()` usage is not overreported.\n22. As a Solid developer, I want component setup conditionals to be flagged when they look like reactive branching, so that I use Solid control flow intentionally.\n23. As a Solid developer, I want diagnostics to explain why Solid components usually run once, so that I understand why the pattern is risky.\n24. As a Solid developer, I want suggestions that mention the intended Solid primitive, so that I know whether to use a prop accessor, memo, resource, cleanup, control-flow component, or client-only boundary.\n25. As a Solid developer, I want false-positive guidance in every rule, so that I can suppress deliberate code responsibly.\n26. As a Solid developer, I want suppression comments to be supported, so that exceptional cases can be documented without disabling an entire rule.\n27. As a library author, I want stricter mode for published packages, so that code shipped to users has stronger correctness guarantees.\n28. As a library author, I want the tool to check example code and docs snippets, so that users do not copy broken Solid patterns.\n29. As a component library author, I want owner cleanup and SSR rules to be especially strict, so that primitives are safe in many app contexts.\n30. As a maintainer, I want a JSON report, so that I can build custom dashboards or integrate with other tools.\n31. As a maintainer, I want a SARIF report, so that diagnostics can appear in code-scanning systems.\n32. As a maintainer, I want a Markdown summary, so that CI can post a readable pull-request comment.\n33. As a maintainer, I want diff mode, so that legacy issues do not block incremental adoption.\n34. As a maintainer, I want changed-line filtering, so that PR comments focus on what the contributor can act on.\n35. As a maintainer, I want configurable score thresholds, so that CI can fail only when health drops below an agreed budget.\n36. As a maintainer, I want category-specific thresholds, so that critical reactivity bugs can fail CI even if the overall score is acceptable.\n37. As a maintainer, I want severity overrides, so that my team can align the tool with our standards.\n38. As a maintainer, I want rule packs, so that I can enable only reactivity rules, only SSR rules, or only library-author rules.\n39. As a monorepo maintainer, I want per-package profiles and scores, so that a bad package does not hide inside a large workspace average.\n40. As a monorepo maintainer, I want project classification, so that Solid apps, Solid libraries, scripts, and tests are analyzed differently.\n41. As a developer using Oxlint, I want Solid Doctor to integrate with my existing Oxlint workflow, so that I do not need to return to ESLint.\n42. As a developer using oxfmt, I want Solid Doctor to avoid formatting opinions, so that formatting remains a separate concern.\n43. As a developer, I want fast scans, so that I can run Solid Doctor during local development without friction.\n44. As a developer, I want a verbose mode, so that I can understand how the tool classified my project and why a rule fired.\n45. As a developer, I want an explain command for each rule, so that I can learn the rule without searching external docs.\n46. As a developer, I want diagnostics to include canonical Solid references, so that recommendations are credible.\n47. As a developer, I want config initialization, so that I can adopt recommended settings without writing everything manually.\n48. As a developer, I want a baseline mode, so that an existing project can record known issues and fail only on regressions.\n49. As a developer, I want autofixes where safe, so that straightforward transformations can be handled automatically.\n50. As a developer, I want unsafe fixes to be clearly marked, so that I do not let the tool rewrite semantic code blindly.\n51. As an AI coding-agent user, I want Solid Doctor to install Solid-specific agent instructions, so that future generated code follows Solid’s mental model.\n52. As an AI coding-agent user, I want agent instructions to include project-specific conventions, so that the agent does not generate generic or incompatible Solid code.\n53. As an AI coding-agent user, I want machine-readable diagnostics, so that agents can fix issues programmatically.\n54. As an AI coding-agent user, I want the tool to identify likely AI-generated React-shaped mistakes, so that I can review generated code more efficiently.\n55. As a team lead, I want a health trend over time, so that I can see whether Solid code quality is improving or degrading.\n56. As a team lead, I want onboarding docs generated from the enabled rules, so that new developers learn the project’s Solid standards.\n57. As an open-source maintainer, I want a public badge or score summary, so that contributors understand the expected quality bar.\n58. As an open-source maintainer, I want contributors to see actionable PR annotations, so that review comments are spent on product decisions instead of repeated Solid basics.\n59. As a rule author, I want a stable test harness for rule fixtures, so that I can add new diagnostics confidently.\n60. As a rule author, I want access to a shared reactive source model, so that every rule does not need to rediscover signals, stores, props, and resources.\n61. As a rule author, I want access to a shared tracking-scope analyzer, so that complex reactivity rules are consistent.\n62. As a rule author, I want rule metadata to power docs, CLI output, JSON output, and agent instructions, so that documentation does not drift.\n63. As a rule author, I want performance benchmarks, so that new rules do not make the tool too slow.\n64. As a rule author, I want false-positive fixtures, so that the tool remains trusted.\n65. As a Solid ecosystem contributor, I want Solid Doctor to complement existing Solid lint plugins, so that prior ecosystem work is reused instead of replaced unnecessarily.\n66. As a Solid ecosystem contributor, I want Solid Doctor’s vocabulary to become shared language, so that docs, tools, libraries, and AI rules describe mistakes consistently.\n67. As a Solid educator, I want examples from diagnostics to teach the reactive graph, so that the tool becomes an educational aid.\n68. As a Solid adopter evaluating the ecosystem, I want a polished doctor tool, so that Solid feels serious, maintainable, and team-ready.\n\n## Implementation Decisions\n\n1. **The product will be Oxlint-first.** The default developer story is `oxfmt` for formatting, `oxlint` for general linting, and Solid Doctor for Solid-specific correctness and health reporting.\n2. **The product will include an Oxlint-compatible plugin layer.** Initial rules can be implemented through Oxlint’s JavaScript plugin compatibility where appropriate, with a future path to native Oxlint rules for performance-sensitive diagnostics.\n3. **The product will not be ESLint-first.** Existing ESLint-oriented Solid rules are important prior art, but the product identity and developer workflow should be built around Oxlint.\n4. **The CLI is the primary product surface.** Users should get useful output from one command before understanding rule packs, config, or integrations.\n5. **The rule engine and doctor layer will be separated.** Rule detection should not know about health-score math, CI markdown, agent installation, or terminal UI.\n6. **The scoring engine will be independent from rules.** Rules produce normalized diagnostics; scoring weights them based on severity, confidence, category, and project context.\n7. **The project classifier will run before rule selection.** SSR-specific rules should not fire blindly in non-SSR contexts, and library-specific rules should be stricter where appropriate.\n8. **Rule metadata will be centralized.** Each rule should define category, severity default, confidence default, docs slug, explanation, remediation, examples, false-positive guidance, and whether autofix is safe.\n9. **The reactive source model will be shared.** All rules that need to identify signals, stores, resources, props, memos, accessors, and user-configured reactive primitives should query the same module.\n10. **The tracking scope analyzer will be shared.** All rules that need to understand tracked reads, untracked reads, async boundaries, JSX bindings, effects, memos, resources, and event handlers should query the same module.\n11. **Diagnostics will include confidence.** Some patterns are definitely wrong; others are suspicious. The UI should expose this distinction.\n12. **The product will support suppressions.** Suppressions should require a rule name and optionally a reason, so teams can audit them.\n13. **Autofix will be conservative.** Safe fixes are allowed; semantic rewrites that require human judgment should be suggestions, not automatic edits.\n14. **Agent installation is a first-class feature.** The product should generate instructions for common coding-agent surfaces and update them safely.\n15. **CI adoption will support baselines and diff mode.** Existing large codebases should not need to fix everything before using the tool.\n16. **The tool will provide multiple reporters.** Terminal output is for local use; JSON is for automation; SARIF/GitHub/Markdown are for CI; agent-readable output is for AI workflows.\n17. **The docs will be rule-driven.** Every rule page should come from the same metadata used by the CLI, minimizing drift.\n18. **The product will avoid formatting.** No formatting diagnostics, no stylistic whitespace rules, and no conflict with `oxfmt`.\n19. **The product will explicitly complement `eslint-plugin-solid`.** The PRD does not require replacing that project; Solid Doctor should reuse, port, wrap, or extend prior art where appropriate.\n20. **The optimal end-state includes native performance later, but not at the cost of delayed product learning.** Start with the fastest path that validates rule value and product UX; optimize hot paths after adoption.\n\n## Testing Decisions\n\nA good Solid Doctor test checks externally observable behavior: given a project profile, configuration, and source fixture, the tool produces the expected normalized diagnostics, score, reports, and fix suggestions. Tests should not over-specify internal AST traversal unless the traversal is itself a public module contract.\n\n### Modules to Test\n\n1. **Project Classifier**\n   - Detects Solid, SolidStart, library, monorepo, test, and generated-code contexts.\n   - Handles missing config, unusual package managers, and mixed workspaces.\n\n2. **Reactive Source Model**\n   - Detects imported Solid primitives.\n   - Tracks aliases.\n   - Understands props, stores, signals, resources, memos, and user-configured primitives.\n   - Avoids classifying unrelated functions as reactive sources.\n\n3. **Tracking Scope Analyzer**\n   - Distinguishes setup, JSX, effect, memo, resource, event handler, callback, async-after-await, and untracked contexts.\n   - Produces stable answers for multiple rules.\n\n4. **Rule Implementations**\n   - Each rule has valid fixtures, invalid fixtures, false-positive fixtures, and optional fix fixtures.\n   - Each rule tests TypeScript and TSX variants where relevant.\n   - Each rule tests import aliasing and common project conventions.\n\n5. **Diagnostic Normalizer**\n   - Deduplicates overlapping findings.\n   - Preserves severity, confidence, category, docs slug, location, and remediation.\n\n6. **Scoring Engine**\n   - Scores are stable across equivalent projects.\n   - Critical issues affect score more than warnings.\n   - Diff mode and baselines affect score predictably.\n   - Large projects are not unfairly punished solely for size.\n\n7. **Reporter System**\n   - Terminal output is readable.\n   - JSON is stable and versioned.\n   - SARIF is valid.\n   - Markdown/GitHub annotations are concise and actionable.\n\n8. **Agent Instruction Installer**\n   - Detects supported agent targets.\n   - Updates existing instructions without unsafe overwrites.\n   - Can run in dry-run mode.\n   - Produces deterministic output from rule metadata.\n\n9. **CLI Integration**\n   - Runs successfully in minimal Solid app fixtures.\n   - Runs successfully in SolidStart fixtures.\n   - Supports config init, score-only output, JSON output, diff mode, explain mode, and CI mode.\n\n10. **Performance Harness**\n    - Measures cold and warm runs.\n    - Tracks rule-level cost.\n    - Prevents accidental performance regressions.\n\n### Fixture Strategy\n\nThe fixture suite should include:\n\n- Minimal valid Solid app.\n- Minimal valid SolidStart app.\n- Component library fixture.\n- Monorepo fixture.\n- React-shaped Solid fixture full of deliberate mistakes.\n- AI-generated Solid fixture to test likely LLM patterns.\n- SSR/browser-global fixture.\n- Async/resource fixture.\n- Owner cleanup fixture.\n- Store and props destructuring fixture.\n- False-positive fixture with deliberate advanced patterns and suppressions.\n\n### Testing Philosophy\n\n- Prefer golden diagnostic snapshots for user-facing output.\n- Prefer normalized diagnostic object tests for rule behavior.\n- Prefer fixture projects over tiny isolated snippets when context matters.\n- Keep rule tests easy to add; contributors should be able to create a new rule test without understanding the entire CLI.\n- Add regression fixtures for every reported false positive.\n\n## Out of Scope\n\n1. Formatting or style formatting. `oxfmt` remains responsible for formatting.\n2. Replacing all general-purpose lint rules from Oxlint.\n3. Becoming an ESLint-first plugin.\n4. Guaranteeing complete runtime correctness for all Solid code.\n5. Building a visual reactive graph devtool in the first product line.\n6. Building a full Solid compiler or runtime instrumentation system.\n7. Automatically rewriting complex reactive code without human review.\n8. Enforcing one team’s styling, component architecture, or design-system preferences.\n9. Policing every performance micro-optimization.\n10. Becoming a component library, UI registry, or SolidStart SaaS template.\n11. Supporting every Solid ecosystem library on day one.\n12. Supporting every editor integration directly before the CLI and CI surfaces are strong.\n13. Publishing health scores externally unless the user explicitly opts in.\n\n## Further Notes\n\n### Recommended MVP Slice from This End-State\n\nAlthough this PRD defines the optimal end-state, the first vertical slice should prove the product’s core thesis:\n\n1. CLI runs one command.\n2. Project classifier detects a Solid/SolidStart project.\n3. Oxlint-compatible rule plugin runs.\n4. Five high-signal rules ship:\n   - Reactive prop/store snapshot.\n   - Derived state in effects.\n   - Async tracking gap after `await`.\n   - Dynamic reactive `.map()` in JSX.\n   - Browser globals in SSR-capable paths.\n5. Diagnostics are normalized and scored.\n6. Terminal and JSON reporters work.\n7. Agent instruction installer writes Solid-specific guidance.\n8. Fixture harness proves true positives and false-positive safety.\n\n### Recommended Branding\n\nPrimary name: **Solid Doctor**  \nPackage/command candidates: `solid-doctor`, `@solid-doctor/cli`, `@solid-doctor/oxlint-plugin`  \nTagline candidates:\n\n- “Oxlint-fast diagnostics for React-shaped Solid.”\n- “Your AI writes React-shaped Solid. Solid Doctor catches it.”\n- “Code health for Solid’s reactive graph.”\n\n### Recommended Rule Documentation Template\n\nEach rule should include:\n\n- Rule name.\n- Category.\n- Default severity.\n- What it detects.\n- Why it matters in Solid.\n- Common bad pattern.\n- Preferred Solid pattern.\n- When the pattern is safe.\n- How to suppress deliberately.\n- Whether autofix is available.\n- Related rules.\n- Canonical Solid references.\n\n### Recommended Rule Priority\n\n1. Reactive snapshots.\n2. Async tracking gaps.\n3. Derived-state effects.\n4. Browser globals in SSR-capable paths.\n5. Dynamic reactive `.map()` in JSX.\n6. Missing cleanup.\n7. Create-root leaks.\n8. Store destructuring and broad store tracking.\n9. Fetch-in-effect for critical data.\n10. Component setup conditionals.\n\n### Recommended Contributor Guidance\n\nContributors should add new rules only when:\n\n- The pattern is likely to cause real Solid correctness, SSR, lifecycle, or maintainability issues.\n- The rule can explain the Solid mental model clearly.\n- False positives can be controlled through context, confidence, config, or suppressions.\n- The rule has both invalid and valid fixtures.\n- The rule can be documented in a way useful to humans and agents.\n\n### Open Questions for Later Product Decisions\n\nThese do not block the PRD but should be resolved before implementation issues are cut:\n\n1. Which Oxlint plugin API surface is stable enough for the first release?\n2. How much type-aware analysis should ship in the first version?\n3. Should existing `eslint-plugin-solid` rules be wrapped, ported, reimplemented, or treated only as inspiration?\n4. What should the default score threshold be for CI?\n5. How should Solid Doctor handle Solid 2.0 changes if they affect reactivity APIs or idioms?\n6. What exact suppression syntax should be supported?\n7. Which agent instruction targets should be supported first?\n8. Should the product include dead-code/dependency health in the first release, or stay strictly Solid-specific?\n9. Should rule documentation be generated into a website from metadata immediately, or start as package docs?\n10. Should the CLI publish anonymous usage metrics? Default answer should be no unless there is a compelling opt-in design.\n\n## References\n\n- Matt Pocock `to-prd` skill: https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/blob/main/skills/engineering/to-prd/SKILL.md\n- AI Hero explanation of `to-prd`: https://www.aihero.dev/skills-to-prd\n- React Doctor: https://github.com/millionco/react-doctor\n- React Doctor docs: https://millionco-react-doctor-36.mintlify.app/introduction\n- Oxlint JS plugins: https://oxc.rs/docs/guide/usage/linter/js-plugins\n- Solid props docs: https://docs.solidjs.com/concepts/components/props\n- Solid `createEffect` docs: https://docs.solidjs.com/reference/basic-reactivity/create-effect\n- Solid `runWithOwner` docs: https://docs.solidjs.com/reference/reactive-utilities/run-with-owner\n- `eslint-plugin-solid`: https://github.com/solidjs-community/eslint-plugin-solid\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/erik-kroon/solid-doctor/issues/1/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vitejs/vite/issues/22057","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vitejs/vite","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vitejs/vite/issues/22057/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vitejs/vite/issues/22057/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vitejs/vite/issues/22057/events","html_url":"https://github.com/vitejs/vite/issues/22057","id":4158042864,"node_id":"I_kwDOD1jqbs731rLw","number":22057,"title":"[Vite 8] Dependency scanner fails with react/jsx-dev-runtime when scanning .tsx entry from node_modules in non-React projects","user":{"login":"birkskyum","id":74932975,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjc0OTMyOTc1","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/74932975?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum","html_url":"https://github.com/birkskyum","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/birkskyum/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[{"id":2060620968,"node_id":"MDU6TGFiZWwyMDYwNjIwOTY4","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vitejs/vite/labels/pending%20triage","name":"pending triage","color":"B3C4DD","default":false,"description":""}],"state":"closed","locked":true,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":1,"created_at":"2026-03-28T06:22:20Z","updated_at":"2026-04-20T00:59:37Z","closed_at":"2026-04-05T14:26:31Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","issue_field_values":[],"type":{"id":12440867,"node_id":"IT_kwDOA-leDM4AvdUj","name":"Bug","description":"An unexpected problem or behavior","color":"red","created_at":"2024-02-04T19:46:56Z","updated_at":"2024-07-26T13:17:10Z","is_enabled":true},"active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"### Describe the bug\n\nVite 8's Rolldown-based dependency scanner injects an implicit react/jsx-dev-runtime import when processing .tsx files listed in optimizeDeps.entries. This breaks projects that use a non-React JSX framework (e.g. SolidJS) when a dependency ships .tsx source files containing JSX.\n\nThis worked in Vite 7 (esbuild-based scanner) and regressed in Vite 8.\n\nThe dependency scanner should not assume React JSX for .tsx files, or should respect the JSX configuration set by framework plugins (like vite-plugin-solid).\n\nThe closest issue I've been able to find is:\n- https://github.com/vitejs/rolldown-vite/issues/304\n\n---\n\n**I tried triage with the AI, which identified the issue as:**\n\nIn prepareRolldownScanner, the transformOptions.jsx defaults to {} when unset ([node.js:30593-30594](https://github.com/vitejs/vite/blob/main/packages/vite/src/node/optimizer/scan.ts)). Rolldown interprets this as React automatic JSX, injecting react/jsx-dev-runtime. The vite-plugin-solid transform runs at serve-time but doesn't participate in the scanner's Rolldown build.\n\n### Reproduction\n\nhttps://stackblitz.com/~/github.com/birkskyum/vite-8-non-react-tsx-repro\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nIt'll show the error on that repro link.\n\nTo verify this is only vite 8, you can in package.json set it to vite 7, and run `npm i` `npm run dev`, then it'll not complain.\n\n### System Info\n\n```shell\nnpx envinfo --system --npmPackages '{vite,@vitejs/*,rollup,rolldown}' --binaries --browsers\n\n  System:\n    OS: macOS 26.4\n    CPU: (10) arm64 Apple M1 Max\n    Memory: 521.66 MB / 64.00 GB\n    Shell: 5.9 - /bin/zsh\n  Binaries:\n    Node: 24.14.1 - /Users/admin/.vite-plus/js_runtime/node/24.14.1/bin/node\n    Yarn: 4.5.1 - /Users/admin/.local/share/mise/shims/yarn\n    npm: 11.11.0 - /Users/admin/.vite-plus/js_runtime/node/24.14.1/bin/npm\n    pnpm: 10.8.0 - /Users/admin/Library/pnpm/pnpm\n    bun: 1.3.9 - /Users/admin/.bun/bin/bun\n    Deno: 2.6.5 - /Users/admin/.deno/bin/deno\n  Browsers:\n    Brave Browser: 144.1.86.146\n    Chrome: 146.0.7680.164\n    Chrome Canary: 144.0.7543.0\n    Firefox: 149.0\n    Safari: 26.4\n  npmPackages:\n    vite: ^8.0.0 => 8.0.3\n```\n\n### Used Package Manager\n\nnpm\n\n### Logs\n\nThe error i see is:\n\n```\n  VITE v8.0.3  ready in 177 ms\n\n  ➜  Local:   http://localhost:5173/\n  ➜  Network: use --host to expose\n  ➜  press h + enter to show help\n(!) Failed to run dependency scan. Skipping dependency pre-bundling. Error: The following dependencies are imported but could not be resolved:\n\n  react/jsx-dev-runtime (imported by /Users/admin/repos/vite-8-tsx-repro/node_modules/pkg-using-solid/index.tsx)\n\nAre they installed?\n```\n\n### Validations\n\n- [x] Follow our [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/vitejs/vite/blob/main/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)\n- [x] Read the [Contributing Guidelines](https://github.com/vitejs/vite/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).\n- [x] Read the [docs](https://vite.dev/guide).\n- [x] Check that there isn't [already an issue](https://github.com/vitejs/vite/issues) that reports the same bug to avoid creating a duplicate.\n- [x] Make sure this is a Vite issue and not 